result.execSummary:
The defendant Molly Ann Nessman was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Controlled Substance, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Court questions defendant on preliminary hearing. Defendant gives responses, freely, voluntarily, and intelligently waives the right to the preliminary hearing. Court accepts the waiver. Court finds probable cause exists that a crime was committed and binds DE over for trial. Defendant enters a NO CONTEST plea to Ct. 1 in case 22CF07 and Ct's 1 and 3 in case 22CF23 therefore it is ordered that Ct's 2 and 3 in case 22CF07 and Ct. 2 in case 22CF23 are DIMISSED and READ IN. DA Kelz states Victim Rights Legislations have been complied with. Court questions DE regarding the plea. DA explains elements of charge.  Court finds plea/waiver to be free, etc.  Court finds factual basis does exist.  Court accepts plea, finds DE guilty and orders entry of JOC.
